---
// Beginner's Hub — a timed first-session practice plan.
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../styles/pages/BeginnersHubPage.css';
import { pageSeo } from '../seo/pages.js';
import { buildWebPageJsonLd } from '../seo/meta.js';
import ContentAnchorSidebar from '../components/ContentAnchorSidebar.astro';
import { siteStats } from '../data/site-meta.js';

const seo = pageSeo.beginnersHub;
const pageJsonLd = buildWebPageJsonLd({
	name: seo.title,
	description: seo.description,
	path: '/beginners-hub',
});
---

<BaseLayout title={seo.title} description={seo.description} keywords={seo.keywords} jsonLd={pageJsonLd}>
	<div class="BeginnersHubPage anchored-page" data-anchor-page>
		<section class="inner-hero-section">
			<div class="container">
				<div class="inner-hero-content">
					<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
						<ol class="breadcrumb-list">
							<li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
							<li><span aria-current="page">Beginner's Hub</span></li>
						</ol>
					</nav>
					<span class="section-label">First-Session Plan</span>
					<h1>Your First 30 Minutes in MECCHA CHAMELEON</h1>
					<p class="page-intro">
						Follow four focused rounds instead of trying to master every map, mode, and paint control at once.
						The goal is a repeatable routine you can use in any {siteStats.playerRange}-player lobby.
					</p>
					<div class="inner-hero-meta">
						<span>10 min read</span><span>{siteStats.currentVersion}</span><span>Four-round plan</span>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

		<!-- compliance:beginner:start -->
		<div class="anchored-page-body">
			<div class="anchored-page-content">
				<section class="inner-content-section">
					<div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block">
						<h2>Use this page as a session plan</h2>
						<p>
							This hub answers one practical question: what should you do during your first half hour with
							MECCHA CHAMELEON? It is not a complete rules reference. Your first objective is to finish a short
							learning loop as both roles, notice one useful clue, and review the result before changing maps or
							settings. A private room with patient friends is ideal, but the same plan works in a public lobby if
							you keep each round simple.
						</p>
						<p>
							If you need exact win conditions, role transitions, mode differences, or an explanation of Spoid,
							pose, paint, and tagging systems, <a href="/guides/meccha-chameleon-how-to-play">Read the complete rules and mode differences</a>.
							Return here when you are ready to turn those systems into a four-round routine.
						</p>
					</div></div>
				</section>

				<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

				<section class="inner-content-section is-alt">
					<div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block is-wide">
						<h2>Minutes 0–5: prepare before joining</h2>
						<p>
							Open Settings before a live round. Confirm that movement and camera input respond, find the prompts
							for the paint and pose menus, and choose a camera sensitivity that lets you make small Seeker scans.
							Do not spend this first session rebuilding every key binding. If a controller is not behaving, use the
							<a href="/guides/meccha-chameleon-controls-settings">controls and settings guide</a> before holding up a lobby.
						</p>
						<ul>
							<li>Choose a stable official map or a Workshop stage the host has already tested privately.</li>
							<li>Use Normal mode while the group is learning fixed Hider and Seeker responsibilities.</li>
							<li>Agree that the results screen is part of practice, not a signal to rush into the next round.</li>
							<li>Keep voice chat quiet while someone hides so sound does not replace visual learning.</li>
						</ul>
						<div class="inner-callout">
							<p class="inner-callout-title">Success at minute five</p>
							<p>You can move, look, open the role tools, and explain which map and mode the room will use.</p>
						</div>
					</div></div>
				</section>

				<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

				<section class="inner-content-section">
					<div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block is-wide">
						<h2>Minutes 5–12: play one disciplined Hider round</h2>
						<p>
							For the first Hider round, ignore elaborate patterns and viral spots. Pick a backdrop within roughly
							fifteen seconds so most preparation time remains for silhouette and colour. A wall edge, low prop,
							floor seam, or compact cluster is easier to evaluate than a route that requires climbing through the
							whole map. Look at the spot from the direction a Seeker is likely to approach.
						</p>
						<ol class="inner-steps">
							<li><strong>Spot:</strong> commit to one local backdrop instead of roaming until the timer is nearly gone.</li>
							<li><strong>Pose:</strong> change the body outline before painting so limbs and height fit the nearby shapes.</li>
							<li><strong>Paint:</strong> sample the same material you are hiding against, then add one darker tone for shadow.</li>
							<li><strong>Check:</strong> rotate the camera and inspect the outline from the open side of the route.</li>
							<li><strong>Freeze:</strong> when the hunt begins, do not repair small paint errors with revealing movement.</li>
						</ol>
						<p>
							Your learning target is not survival. After the round, name whether the first visible problem was your
							location, outline, colour, shadow, or movement. One specific answer is more useful than a win you cannot explain.
						</p>
					</div></div>
				</section>

				<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

				<section class="inner-content-section is-alt">
					<div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block is-wide">
						<h2>Minutes 12–18: make one deliberate Seeker sweep</h2>
						<p>
							A first-time Seeker often sprints through the center and repeatedly checks the same obvious objects.
							Slow down and use a route you can remember. Begin at the perimeter, follow one wall, then cross the
							middle only after the outside pass. Pause when a repeated pattern has an extra shape, a flat colour
							blob lacks the expected shadow, or an object has a human-scale outline.
						</p>
						<table class="inner-data-table">
							<thead><tr><th>Pass</th><th>Look for</th><th>Do not do</th></tr></thead>
							<tbody>
								<tr><td>Perimeter</td><td>Corners, wall edges, ceiling lines, and silhouettes against open space</td><td>Zigzag across the center</td></tr>
								<tr><td>Repeated surfaces</td><td>Broken rows, unexpected gaps, wrong-scale shapes, and mismatched finish</td><td>Test every prop randomly</td></tr>
								<tr><td>Return angle</td><td>Outlines hidden from the first direction of travel</td><td>Repeat the same viewing angle</td></tr>
							</tbody>
						</table>
						<p>At the results screen, choose one Hider you missed and identify the approach angle that would have exposed the disguise.</p>
					</div></div>
				</section>

				<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

				<section class="inner-content-section">
					<div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block is-wide">
						<h2>Minutes 18–25: repeat one variable at a time</h2>
						<p>
							Rounds three and four are controlled repeats. Do not change map, mode, backdrop type, paint method,
							and route all at once. A repeat teaches you whether the adjustment helped; a completely new attempt
							only gives you another collection of guesses.
						</p>
						<table class="inner-data-table">
							<thead><tr><th>Round</th><th>Keep constant</th><th>Change one thing</th><th>Question afterward</th></tr></thead>
							<tbody>
								<tr><td>3 — Hider</td><td>Same kind of backdrop and two-tone method</td><td>Use a lower or more compact pose</td><td>Did the outline survive the main approach?</td></tr>
								<tr><td>4 — Seeker</td><td>Same perimeter-first route</td><td>Pause longer on repeated materials</td><td>Which visual break became easier to notice?</td></tr>
							</tbody>
						</table>
						<p>
							If no live room is available, use the <a href="/camouflage-simulator">Camouflage Simulator</a> to
							compare two poses against one background. The separate <a href="/play-game">browser practice experience</a>
							can introduce a lighter paint-and-hide loop, but it is not the official Steam game.
						</p>
					</div></div>
				</section>

				<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

				<section class="inner-content-section is-alt">
					<div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block">
						<h2>Minutes 25–30: write a three-line review</h2>
						<p>
							Finish the session before fatigue turns practice into random play. Record one Hider observation, one
							Seeker observation, and one experiment for next time. For example: “My colour matched, but my upright
							shoulder broke the shelf line. I missed a Hider because I never returned through the doorway. Next
							session I will test a compact pose and one reverse-angle sweep.”
						</p>
						<ul>
							<li>Open one relevant <a href="/wiki#wiki-maps">map note</a>, not the entire library.</li>
							<li>Check <a href="/updates">patch notes</a> if a control, route, or result differs from a guide.</li>
							<li>Use <a href="/online">multiplayer help</a> only if joining, hosting, or invites blocked the session.</li>
							<li>Save advanced paint drills for the next session instead of extending this one indefinitely.</li>
						</ul>
					</div></div>
				</section>

				<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

				<section class="inner-content-section">
					<div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block is-wide">
						<h2>First-session questions</h2>
						<h3>Should I memorize hiding spots before playing?</h3>
						<p>No. Learn how to judge a backdrop and approach angle. Fixed spots become familiar to Seekers and can change after patches.</p>
						<h3>What if I lose all four rounds?</h3>
						<p>The session still worked if you can identify why a disguise failed and which part of your sweep missed a Hider. The plan measures observations, not wins.</p>
						<h3>When should I try Infection or Double?</h3>
						<p>After everyone can describe the fixed-role loop. Read the <a href="/guides/meccha-chameleon-how-to-play">rules and mechanics reference</a> before changing modes.</p>
						<h3>What should I practise next?</h3>
						<p>Choose the weakest item in your three-line review: silhouette, two-tone paint, stillness, perimeter routing, or reverse-angle checks. Practise only that item first.</p>
					</div></div>
				</section>

				<div data-gpt-banner-anchor></div>

				<section class="cta-section">
					<div class="container">
						<h2>Choose one next step</h2>
						<p>Move from the timed plan to the reference or practice tool that answers the question you recorded.</p>
						<div class="cta-actions">
							<a class="btn btn-primary" href="/guides/meccha-chameleon-how-to-play">Rules & Mechanics</a>
							<a class="btn btn-outline btn-outline-light" href="/camouflage-simulator">Camouflage Simulator</a>
							<a class="btn btn-outline btn-outline-light" href="/wiki#wiki-maps">Wiki Maps</a>
						</div>
					</div>
				</section>
			</div>
			<ContentAnchorSidebar />
		</div>
		<!-- compliance:beginner:end -->
	</div>
</BaseLayout>
